06:02.571 --> 06:04.948
The banjo ain't my bag,
but this dude can play.

06:05.074 --> 06:07.907
Don Vappie? Oh, yeah.

06:08.035 --> 06:10.117
I've always been down
with traditional myself.

06:10.246 --> 06:13.864
Yeah, I noticed, but you old school
and cutting edge at the same time.

06:13.999 --> 06:17.787
That's New Orleans, young man.
Many styles, many traditions.

06:17.920 --> 06:20.161
Yeah, but for me traditional is Bird and Diz

06:20.297 --> 06:24.711
playing Salt Peanuts at Massey Hall
with Bud Powell and Max Roach.

06:24.843 --> 06:27.425
— And Charles Mingus on bass.
— Right, exactly!

06:27.555 --> 06:29.841
One, two, three. Yeah!

06:31.183 --> 06:32.923
Come on, y'all. Keep goin', come on!

06:33.060 --> 06:35.927
I'll tell you what,
let's go up here and do our set,

06:36.063 --> 06:37.928
but end with a little something from home.

06:38.065 --> 06:39.726
Like what?

06:39.858 --> 06:43.225
lko, Mardi Gras Mambo,

06:43.362 --> 06:45.273
Saints.

06:45.406 --> 06:48.443
You gotta give the good people of Arizona
a little of what they came to hear.

06:48.576 --> 06:50.567
Just play our set, man.

07:09.597 --> 07:11.212
Mr. Dietrich?

07:11.348 --> 07:13.760
Jim Dietrich? l'm Toni Bernette.

07:13.892 --> 07:17.134
I'm a lawyer from New Orleans, and I need
to talk to you for a minute, if I may.

07:17.271 --> 07:19.603
It's not about NOPD.

07:19.732 --> 07:21.723
I'm looking for somebody who's missing,

07:21.859 --> 07:26.319
and I drove all this way
hoping you'd be able to help me.

07:29.575 --> 07:33.033
(Taxicab radio chatter)

07:35.789 --> 07:39.077
— Hey, Angie.
— Hey, Antoine.

07:39.209 --> 07:41.370
— How you doing?
— Good, baby. How are you?

07:41.503 --> 07:43.368
I'm good.

07:43.505 --> 07:46.042
- What you got there?
— It's a little something for your daddy.

07:46.175 --> 07:49.042
— Oh, yeah? He's inside.
- (Both) Mwah!

07:49.178 --> 07:51.965
(J‘ Music playing quietly)

07:52.097 --> 07:54.588
That's a real fine horn.

07:54.725 --> 07:56.681
To replace the one you lost in the flood.

07:56.810 --> 07:59.347
It's beautiful, Daddy.

07:59.480 --> 08:02.972
I can't. This must have cost a fortune.

08:03.108 --> 08:04.484
See, I didn't buy it.

08:04.610 --> 08:06.316
Somebody bought it for you.

08:06.445 --> 08:09.187
Yeah, a jazz fan. Japanese cat.

08:09.323 --> 08:12.030
Come through town, looking to do good
for New Orleans musicians, right?

08:12.159 --> 08:15.196
I told him about your situation
and he knew all about you.

08:15.329 --> 08:17.194
Yeah, big fan.

08:17.331 --> 08:20.243
He said it was the least he could do.

08:20.376 --> 08:22.708
- An honor.
— I don't know.

08:22.836 --> 08:24.997
I ain't felt much like blowing, you know?

08:25.130 --> 08:26.870
That's because you ain't had one to blow.

08:27.007 --> 08:30.545
Now look here, maestro,
that thing needs to make noise.

08:30.678 --> 08:32.714
I don't know what to say.

08:32.846 --> 08:34.382
Like you always told me.

08:34.515 --> 08:38.349
Straight ahead and strive for tone.

08:43.399 --> 08:46.141
Spoken to every officer
from the Second District

08:46.276 --> 08:48.767
who worked the midnight to eight shift
that Sunday.

08:48.904 --> 08:51.111
Well, everybody except for you

08:51.240 --> 08:53.401
and Bobby Foskett.

08:53.534 --> 08:56.401
- (Thunder rumbling)
— Why Second District?

08:56.537 --> 08:59.574
A young man I'm looking for
lived on Valence Street,

08:59.707 --> 09:02.744
and the restaurant he worked at
is at Laurel and Webster.

09:02.876 --> 09:04.537
OK.

09:04.670 --> 09:06.752
Well, his boss asked him
to do something at the restaurant

09:06.880 --> 09:09.132
that morning just before the storm blew in.

09:09.258 --> 09:10.748
He never showed.

09:10.884 --> 09:13.296
My best guess,
he was stopped on the way there.

09:13.429 --> 09:15.590
— (Thunder)
— That's thin.

09:15.723 --> 09:18.305
(Chuckles) That's what I've got.

09:18.434 --> 09:21.597
So you talked to everyone else
in the 12 to eight,

09:21.729 --> 09:24.812
and it's down to me and Bobby Foskett.

09:24.940 --> 09:28.933
— And Bobby Foskett's dead.
— You heard?

09:29.069 --> 09:32.732
Ate his gun a month after the storm.

09:36.076 --> 09:38.237
Still don't know how you found me.

09:38.370 --> 09:41.112
You had your last check sent
to your sister's here in Port Arthur.

09:41.248 --> 09:44.536
After that, it was easy.
I just called the utility company.

09:47.004 --> 09:49.620
Only had a couple of traffic stops
that morning.

09:49.757 --> 09:54.046
When the storm blew in,
we had our fuckin' hands full.

09:57.931 --> 10:01.344
I pulled over a black male
about this guy's age,

10:01.477 --> 10:03.968
blew through the light
at Nashville and Tchoupitoulas.

10:04.104 --> 10:05.935
Blew through it right in front of me,

10:06.064 --> 10:08.100
so I had to hit the blue tops,

10:08.233 --> 10:10.269
give him a ticket.

10:12.988 --> 10:14.649
This young man?

10:14.782 --> 10:17.194
Could be. I don't know.

10:17.326 --> 10:19.567
This matters.

10:19.703 --> 10:21.910
I need a positive ID for the habeas.

10:22.039 --> 10:24.121
I need you to be sure.

10:25.959 --> 10:28.291
That was five months ago.

10:28.420 --> 10:30.331
And let's be honest,

10:30.464 --> 10:33.627
he looks like a lot of guys
I've written up over the years.

10:35.469 --> 10:36.925
I'm sorry.

10:37.054 --> 10:39.340
lwish I could help.

10:39.473 --> 10:41.589
But that was another life.

10:41.725 --> 10:43.090
I'm done with NOPD.

10:43.227 --> 10:45.309
Done with New Orleans too,
for what it's worth.

10:48.190 --> 10:50.897
— That's me.
— (J‘ Band playing)

10:51.026 --> 10:52.562
You don't have to take that.

10:52.694 --> 10:54.605
— Cray, it's on wheels.
- No problem.

10:54.738 --> 10:58.196
We're just across the way,
short-term parking.

10:58.325 --> 11:00.907
You didn't need to pick me up.
I'd have taken a cab.

11:01.036 --> 11:02.947
Don't be silly.

11:03.080 --> 11:05.867
My agent comes
all the way from New York...

11:05.999 --> 11:08.376
I'm so glad to see you, Cray.

11:08.502 --> 11:12.211
You should come to New York more often.
How long has it been?

11:12.339 --> 11:14.375
Carla, level with me, will ya?

11:14.508 --> 11:16.464
They want their advance back, don't they?

11:16.593 --> 11:19.335
I know they haven't forgotten about it.

11:19.972 --> 11:23.715
I know it's just gnawing the guts
out of some bean counter.

11:23.851 --> 11:27.389
There are a couple of things
I wanna talk to you about,

11:27.521 --> 11:29.637
but it's all good.

11:29.773 --> 11:32.606
— Oh.
— I love the band.

11:32.734 --> 11:35.476
The best airport music ever.

11:38.532 --> 11:41.740
Why'd you quit? If you don't mind my asking.

11:41.869 --> 11:45.532
Ma'am, I worked eight straight days
after that storm,

11:45.664 --> 11:48.121
all of it out of my car.

11:48.250 --> 11:50.866
I wore the same uniform, stank like a dog.

11:51.003 --> 11:53.745
Ate, drank what I could scavenge.

11:53.881 --> 11:57.044
At some point I just had to wonder why.

11:58.802 --> 12:02.090
My house was underwater,
everything I owned with it.

12:02.222 --> 12:04.304
It ain't like I'm too old
to do something else, you know?

12:04.433 --> 12:05.673
Mm.

12:05.809 --> 12:08.016
ljust had enough.

12:10.522 --> 12:14.765
— What are you going to do now?
— My brother's in Corpus with the union,

12:14.902 --> 12:17.609
gonna get me some work offshore.

12:17.738 --> 12:20.855
— Good luck.
- You too.

12:23.994 --> 12:27.407
Sorry I can't put a face
to that Tchoupitoulas stop.

12:27.539 --> 12:30.827
| feel bad it was me
who got your friend lost in the sauce.

12:36.506 --> 12:39.418
The young man on Tchoupitoulas
who ran a red light.

12:39.551 --> 12:41.928
— You said you wrote him a ticket.
— I had to.

12:42.054 --> 12:44.045
He blew through the light
right in front of me.

12:44.181 --> 12:47.423
— But you didn't lock him up, right?
— Yeah, he got locked up.

12:48.393 --> 12:50.008
Wait, wait.

12:50.145 --> 12:52.431
You arrested him for running a red light?

12:52.564 --> 12:54.520
No, for the warrant.

12:56.234 --> 12:57.895
The warrant?

13:00.364 --> 13:02.776
Guess we're not done.

13:03.992 --> 13:06.779
(Creighton) Carla, I thought Random House
wrote me off a long time ago.

13:06.912 --> 13:08.777
Maybe they did, to a certain extent,

13:08.914 --> 13:12.577
but Katrina has put New Orleans
back on the map in a certain way.

13:12.709 --> 13:15.917
(Chuckles) lt nearly wiped it
off the map, actually.

13:16.713 --> 13:20.001
The near—death of an American city
and now my publisher's hot for a book

13:20.133 --> 13:22.249
they couldn't care less about
six months ago.

13:22.386 --> 13:26.299
Actually, they're not only interested in
bringing your novel out on next fall's list,

13:26.431 --> 13:29.389
but they want you to do something contemporary before
then.

13:29.518 --> 13:32.601
- Contemporary?
— Yeah, those passionate editorials

13:32.729 --> 13:35.106
that you've been doing on the internet?

13:35.232 --> 13:37.018
I showed a couple to your editor

13:37.150 --> 13:40.768
and, uh, Lisa loves that voice from you.

13:40.904 --> 13:43.611
Fuck You, You Fucking Fucks. Nice title.

13:43.740 --> 13:47.528
From serious novelist to cartoon
in one single volume.

13:47.661 --> 13:49.526
No, they'd bring the novel out after.

13:49.663 --> 13:52.200
And if you can manage
to make the novel contemporary,

13:52.332 --> 13:57.702
— maybe set part of it in post—Katrina...
— The novel is about the 1927 flood.

13:57.838 --> 14:00.454
It speaks to the present situation
only as metaphor.

14:00.590 --> 14:03.377
Well, perhaps if you could
bookend some older material...

14:03.510 --> 14:06.843
Jesus Christ, Carla.
I thought you said they wanted the book.

14:06.972 --> 14:09.634
They do, but in the voice
that you have become.

14:09.766 --> 14:11.927
You're a spokesman now for this city.

14:12.060 --> 14:16.474
I'm not trying to be the spokesman of the city. New Orleans
speaks for itself.

14:16.606 --> 14:19.894
And the novel is what it is.
If they still want it, fine.

14:20.027 --> 14:23.110
You haven't published in eight years, Cray.

14:23.238 --> 14:27.151
And now because of the storm,
yes, because of it,

14:27.284 --> 14:30.321
your publisher wants this book desperately.

14:30.454 --> 14:32.695
This is an opportunity.

14:35.042 --> 14:36.953
I'll finish the damn novel.

14:37.085 --> 14:40.543
When? What can I tell them?

14:40.672 --> 14:44.836
I need a month, six weeks maybe.

14:44.968 --> 14:47.584
But it's a novel about the '27 flood.

14:47.721 --> 14:50.633
That's what they bought.
That's what I'm writing.

14:50.766 --> 14:53.508
I checked for warrants on David
when | first began looking for him.

14:53.643 --> 14:55.850
There is nothing on record with any court.

14:55.979 --> 14:58.561
You think I want to lock the man up
with a hurricane coming?

14:58.690 --> 15:00.601
l was gonna let him roll with the traffic ticket,

15:00.734 --> 15:04.443
but how am I gonna cut a guy loose when he's got a
warrant on him for failing to appear?

15:07.282 --> 15:10.774
Radioed for the sergeant to meet me
back at lPC, sign off on the papenNork.

15:10.911 --> 15:13.618
I waited for...must've been an hour,
maybe more.

15:13.747 --> 15:18.116
Finally, I make phone contact with him.
Says he's out of pocket, shit's hitting the fan,

15:18.251 --> 15:20.333
he'd come down
at the end of the shift and sign off.

15:20.462 --> 15:23.204
So I left the guy there.
They said they'd hold him for the sergeant.

15:23.340 --> 15:25.672
And whatever paperwork
you left for the prisoner

15:25.801 --> 15:29.794
goes under ten feet of water
when the jail floods, huh?

15:31.932 --> 15:35.675
The affidavit from your citation book.
There'd be a carbon of it.

15:35.811 --> 15:38.803
— Left it in the car.
— At Second District?

15:38.939 --> 15:41.646
— Lake Charles.
— Lake Charles?

15:41.775 --> 15:43.640
When I left, ljust crawled in my unit

15:43.777 --> 15:46.735
— and drove out of town.
- Why Lake Charles?

15:46.863 --> 15:49.980
You think l was gonna take
an NOPD unit out of Louisiana?

15:50.117 --> 15:54.076
l was in enough trouble taking it out of town, never mind
across state line.

15:54.204 --> 15:57.913
I drove it onto the Lake Charles PD lot,
left the keys at the front desk,

15:58.041 --> 16:00.077
told them to call New Orleans, let 'em know.

16:00.210 --> 16:03.043
Then I got my brother—in—law
to drive over and get me.

16:03.171 --> 16:05.753
Take another look, please?

16:10.720 --> 16:14.258
Sorry. I can't be sure it's him.

16:14.391 --> 16:17.758
I mean, if you want me to be honest about it.

16:26.194 --> 16:28.150
(J‘ Music playing)

16:29.281 --> 16:30.521
You gave him a drink?

16:30.657 --> 16:33.114
(Jacques) All he wanted was a Barq's.

16:33.243 --> 16:35.700
It goes with everything.

16:35.829 --> 16:37.820
Jacques, what am I gonna tell him?

16:37.956 --> 16:39.867
I can't run a restaurant without meat.

16:40.000 --> 16:43.208
I don't even know
how I'm gonna pay staff today.

16:43.336 --> 16:45.588
You can't make payroll?

16:45.714 --> 16:47.250
(Pounding at door)

16:47.382 --> 16:50.465
— Oh, shit. Who's that?
— Seafood.

16:52.095 --> 16:54.461
- (Pounding continues)
— Fuck me.

16:56.016 --> 16:58.507
Give him a Barq's too.

17:04.691 --> 17:06.056
What's up, Jacques?

17:06.193 --> 17:09.731
Uh, Janette had to run out
for a few minutes.

17:09.863 --> 17:13.401
It's funny how everybody all of a sudden
got all these errands they gotta run today.

17:13.533 --> 17:16.491
She has a very busy afternoon.
But if you'd like to wait...

17:16.620 --> 17:19.202
I don't want to, but I will.

17:21.875 --> 17:23.786
(Jacques) What would you like to drink?

17:23.919 --> 17:26.035
Scotch.

17:26.171 --> 17:29.038
- (Door opens)
— (Ben) You too, huh?

17:30.926 --> 17:33.258
Hey, Daddy.

17:33.386 --> 17:36.093
Heard them talking about
your YouTube stuff on the radio.

17:36.223 --> 17:37.759
You're famous.

17:37.891 --> 17:41.725
l'm mentioned. There's a difference.
Was that your mom on the phone?

17:41.853 --> 17:44.230
She said she'd be home
tomorrow morning for sure.

17:44.356 --> 17:46.187
Are we out of milk again?

17:46.316 --> 17:47.806
Right.

17:48.902 --> 17:50.733
"Davis can save us." What is that?

17:50.862 --> 17:52.272
Oh, it's the Davis bumper sticker.

17:52.405 --> 17:54.441
He's running for city council.

17:54.574 --> 17:56.235
Davis McAlary?

17:56.368 --> 17:59.075
Our Davis who's teaching you boogie—woogie?

17:59.204 --> 18:01.445
That bozo's running for council?

18:01.581 --> 18:03.537
J‘ Vote for me, I ain't fakin'

18:05.585 --> 18:07.792
— Hey.
— Mom's not here.

18:07.921 --> 18:10.333
It's not your language. This isn't funny.

18:10.465 --> 18:12.626
What's happening
in New Orleans now is not a joke.

18:12.759 --> 18:15.000
We're fighting for our lives,
for our way of life.

18:15.136 --> 18:17.127
People are dying. People are homeless.

18:17.264 --> 18:20.472
People are stuck all over the place.
They can't get back.

18:20.600 --> 18:22.761
Everything is not a joke all the time.

18:22.894 --> 18:26.512
— You mean like Krewe du Vieux?
— That's political satire.

18:26.648 --> 18:29.890
It's a long tradition. This is just wrong.

18:35.907 --> 18:37.898
(Man) Where's the gaffer?

18:41.663 --> 18:43.528
— Can I help you?
- Yeah.

18:43.665 --> 18:46.828
Davis McAlary,
here for the candidates' forum.

18:48.712 --> 18:50.703
Mm.

18:51.631 --> 18:55.123
McAlary, you are indeed
a registered candidate.

18:55.260 --> 18:57.501
Paid the fees with cash money.

19:01.016 --> 19:03.007
Come with me.

19:05.270 --> 19:08.262
Hold that. Enjoy that.

19:09.316 --> 19:11.181
(J‘ Music playing)

19:11.318 --> 19:13.400
