- Yeah.

19:13.528 --> 19:15.985
Getting me a shitload of those, you know?

19:16.114 --> 19:17.979
That sounds good.

19:21.328 --> 19:23.740
(Coughing)

19:33.048 --> 19:36.085
— He's in Chicago now? Palmer House?
— (Phil Frazier) Yeah.

19:36.217 --> 19:39.345
— And Troy's playing trumpet?
- Like I told you, man.

19:39.471 --> 19:41.678
— You're sure?
— Yeah, I got you.

19:41.806 --> 19:43.762
— All right, I'll call him right now.
- Sure.

19:43.892 --> 19:45.883
Thanks.

19:49.356 --> 19:52.018
— Honey, it's your turn to...
- Sh, sh. Hold on now.

19:52.150 --> 19:54.687
— (Woman) The Palmer House.
— Can I speak to one of your guests?

19:54.819 --> 19:57.526
— Sure. What's the name?
- Yeah, uh, Dr. John.

19:57.655 --> 20:00.943
- Dr. John?
— The musician Dr. John.

20:01.076 --> 20:03.738
— Is there another name he goes by?
— I don't know.

20:03.870 --> 20:06.111
That is his name.
Oh, I know what you're saying.

20:06.247 --> 20:08.829
lt's, um, Mac...

20:08.958 --> 20:12.200
Uh, Mac...

20:12.337 --> 20:13.827
- Aw, shit.
— Sorry, sir.

20:13.963 --> 20:15.578
— No, pardon me.
— No Mac.

20:15.715 --> 20:18.127
— You ain't got a Mac?
— Not registered.

20:18.259 --> 20:20.250
(Softly) Hey, you remember
his real last name?

20:20.387 --> 20:22.719
— Rebennack.
— Rebennack.

20:22.847 --> 20:25.429
— How do you spell that?
- Like it sounds, shit.

20:25.558 --> 20:26.934
— One moment.
- (Silence)

20:27.060 --> 20:29.597
— (Whispers) You're welcome.
—(Beeps)

20:29.729 --> 20:33.267
— (Dr. John) Yeah?
— Yeah, uh, Dr. John,

20:33.400 --> 20:35.812
it's Antoine Batiste
calling from New Orleans.

20:35.944 --> 20:37.480
Hey, Antoine. What's happening?

20:37.612 --> 20:40.900
Uh, yeah, Philip Frazier
told me | oughta call you.

20:41.032 --> 20:43.444
You might need a trombone
to fill in on a tour you're making?

20:43.576 --> 20:45.908
Look, Antoine, I'd love to have you
with the Aggravation,

20:46.037 --> 20:49.450
— but we already got Troy playing slide.
— I thought Troy was playing trumpet.

20:49.582 --> 20:52.824
— Charlie Miller is playing that...
- That motherfucker.

20:52.961 --> 20:57.045
..this time around.
| wish I could hook you up.

20:57.173 --> 20:59.789
Uh, yeah.

20:59.926 --> 21:03.168
Well, that's all right. Thanks.

21:03.304 --> 21:06.512
— Hey, keep me in mind, you know? I could...
- Yeah, you bet.

21:06.641 --> 21:08.427
(Phone clicks)

21:13.898 --> 21:15.980
(Grunts)

21:16.109 --> 21:18.725
Don't worry yet. You'll find something.

21:20.905 --> 21:24.989
(Woman) And, Peggy, that is why I'm the
best candidate for city council, District C.

21:25.118 --> 21:29.031
— Mr. McCleary.
- McAlary.

21:29.164 --> 21:31.997
My apologies. Mr. McAlary.

21:33.084 --> 21:34.824
Oh, um...

21:34.961 --> 21:38.453
Well, first I'd like to sing
some of my campaign song.

21:40.467 --> 21:42.833
— So just...
— l have to ask you to stay within the format.

21:42.969 --> 21:44.709
— No singing.
— (Man laughs)

21:44.846 --> 21:47.553
You have two minutes
for an opening statement.

21:47.682 --> 21:49.593
OK.

21:51.686 --> 21:53.677
(J‘ Playing Yardbird Delight)

22:38.274 --> 22:40.139
(Song ends)

22:40.276 --> 22:42.107
(Applause, cheering)

22:42.237 --> 22:44.569
Thank you, Houston!

22:44.697 --> 22:48.986
Oh, man. Loved that, man. Loved that.

22:49.118 --> 22:50.949
Donald's homage to Bird, man.

22:51.079 --> 22:53.195
- Yeah, you know it?
— You better believe it, baby.

22:53.331 --> 22:55.538
- All right.
— Beautiful!

22:55.667 --> 22:58.500
Thanks, Don. You guys did a great set too.

23:00.046 --> 23:02.002
— Looks like an encore.
— Hey.

23:02.131 --> 23:05.259
— lko.
— You ain't gonna quit?

23:05.385 --> 23:07.421
— You know you like it.
- Aw.

23:07.554 --> 23:10.967
— (J‘ Playing lko lko)
— (Crowd cheering)

23:13.643 --> 23:15.508
(Man) One more time, y'all.

23:15.645 --> 23:17.852
(Woman) Come on, let's hear it again.

23:37.125 --> 23:39.332
(Crowd) J‘ Hey now! Hey now!

23:40.503 --> 23:42.619
(Crowd) J‘ Oh—oh—oh

24:02.775 --> 24:05.517
(Jacques) You want me to lock up?

24:05.653 --> 24:07.814
I don't know.

24:08.990 --> 24:13.324
So it's official now. I'm now on COD
with every one of our suppliers.

24:13.453 --> 24:15.990
COD plus five with Harvey.

24:16.122 --> 24:19.660
COD plus ten with Cusimano.

24:19.792 --> 24:22.625
I can't write rubber checks
and I can't cook without food.

24:23.463 --> 24:24.919
The bank?

24:25.048 --> 24:27.164
I owe them a huge balloon payment.

24:27.300 --> 24:30.042
And I can't go to my parents again.

24:30.178 --> 24:35.263
And the thing is, we're still putting out
a menu every night that I'm proud of.

24:36.684 --> 24:40.552
I mean, we're short, we're tight,
but push comes to shove...

24:40.688 --> 24:44.647
— You killed those chefs.
— l buried 'em, didn't I?

24:44.776 --> 24:46.266
Oui.

24:47.320 --> 24:49.311
(Sighs)

24:54.911 --> 24:57.618
You think the staff can hang in for a week?

24:59.165 --> 25:01.281
Till I can figure out how to deal with this?

25:02.669 --> 25:04.625
Come up with it somewhere?

25:04.754 --> 25:06.745
Without pay?

25:13.304 --> 25:15.260
You can ask.

25:17.517 --> 25:21.055
(Davis) One of my cornerstone programs
is called Greased Palm Sunday.

25:21.187 --> 25:23.769
If we're gonna have corruption,
let's just be honest about it.

25:23.898 --> 25:26.310
So, one Sunday a month,

25:26.442 --> 25:29.559
we will have an official televised session

25:29.696 --> 25:32.813
in which the money be delivered
and the deals made.

25:32.949 --> 25:35.941
— "Real bribes in real time" will be my motto.
- You're right, bro.

25:36.077 --> 25:38.409
Let's have some straight—up,
honest double—dealing.

25:38.538 --> 25:41.826
Sunlight. It's the best disinfectant.

25:41.958 --> 25:44.165
- Well, I'm on.
— (Peggy) Interesting.

25:44.293 --> 25:46.079
McAlary, you're whack.

25:46.212 --> 25:48.248
"Sunlight is the best disinfectant"?

25:48.381 --> 25:50.292
— Yeah, I read that somewhere.
- (Chuckles)

25:50.425 --> 25:52.586
- What, it's not true?
— (Coco) Kill the TV, Janice.

25:52.719 --> 25:54.584
Well, it sounds true.

25:54.721 --> 25:57.258
- (Mutes TV)
— (J‘ Music starts)

25:57.390 --> 26:00.553
J‘ When the time is right on a night in June

26:00.685 --> 26:04.098
J‘ All the hoodoo dance
underneath the moon

26:04.230 --> 26:07.438
J‘ What goes on, child, you better believe

26:07.567 --> 26:11.480
J‘ Way down in New Orlean
on St. John's Eve J‘

26:11.612 --> 26:13.694
(Antoine) Three damn hours on the phone.

26:13.823 --> 26:17.816
I'm ready to play the goddamn zoo
for elephants.

26:17.952 --> 26:19.658
(Kermit) I might have something for you.

26:19.787 --> 26:23.450
- You can read, right?
— I can read flyshit on staff paper.

26:23.583 --> 26:27.667
(Chuckles) You're gonna need a tux.
Carnival time, bro.

26:27.795 --> 26:30.582
— Balls and all.
— The Mardi Gras ball?

26:30.715 --> 26:33.252
— Yeah, like the Bunch Club.
— Really?

26:33.384 --> 26:34.965
Well, LaDonna bought me a tux,

26:35.094 --> 26:37.961
you know, for that tribute
for Duke Dejan and Olympia.

26:38.097 --> 26:42.306
— Yeah. Still got it?
— Must be in a box somewhere.

26:42.435 --> 26:44.642
Who else is on this gig
besides me and you?

26:44.771 --> 26:46.853
Nah, man, I ain't on. But you'll be cool.

26:46.981 --> 26:49.313
Ah. (Chuckles)

26:49.442 --> 26:52.980
I played the MOMs ball once,
sitting in with the Radiators.

26:53.112 --> 26:57.321
It was wild, man, I'm telling you.
The band was playing, you know.

26:57.450 --> 27:01.443
Everybody was screwing every which way.

27:01.579 --> 27:05.288
I guess I could use a little fun myself.
You know what I'm saying?

27:05.416 --> 27:08.453
— Happy Mardi Gras, Batiste.
- Happy Mardi Gras.

27:12.381 --> 27:15.418
(Davis) There's no fuckin' reason
why we gotta have potholes

27:15.551 --> 27:17.212
that can swallow your whole fucking car.

27:17.345 --> 27:20.178
- You feel me?
— He's obsessive about potholes.

27:20.306 --> 27:22.342
Somebody's gotta
call these motherfuckers out.

27:22.475 --> 27:24.966
I agree. You're right.

27:25.102 --> 27:27.639
You agree? Really?

27:27.772 --> 27:31.685
Jacques Morial, scion of a great
political dynasty, agrees with me.

27:31.818 --> 27:34.685
Man, that shit is funny.
Greased Palm Sunday.

27:34.821 --> 27:37.153
Pot for potholes. Don't forget that one.

27:37.281 --> 27:39.021
That's satire. That's good.

27:39.158 --> 27:41.319
But you have a chance
to raise some serious questions

27:41.452 --> 27:43.943
that none of these
other motherfuckers are gonna touch.

27:44.080 --> 27:44.990
I do?

27:45.122 --> 27:47.864
Look, looking ahead here,
we got some serious challenges.

27:48.000 --> 27:51.208
We got public housing,
we got expropriation of people's homes,

27:51.337 --> 27:53.498
we got when they're
gonna reopen Charity Hospital,

27:53.631 --> 27:57.044
and we got this big, nasty question
about who can come home and who can't.

27:57.176 --> 28:02.045
Right. Here's an idea.
Why don't you be my campaign manager?

28:02.181 --> 28:05.048
— Not gonna happen.
- (Laughter)

28:05.184 --> 28:09.769
But, look, what I can do is I can hook you up with some real
effective public exposure

28:09.897 --> 28:12.388
so we can get these issues on the table.

28:12.525 --> 28:14.857
That's if you really wanna kick it up a notch.

28:14.986 --> 28:17.728
— Hell, yeah.
— You should go for it, Davis.

28:21.409 --> 28:23.400
Do you really think I can win this?

28:23.536 --> 28:25.401
The election?

28:25.538 --> 28:26.994
No fuckin' way.

28:28.207 --> 28:29.538
Right.

28:29.667 --> 28:31.658
l was just checking.

28:32.962 --> 28:34.077
It's about time they sent someone.

28:34.213 --> 28:37.876
We've been calling NOPD about that vehicle for three
months now, maybe longer.

28:38.009 --> 28:41.342
The department's still in disarray,
to say the least.

28:41.470 --> 28:43.802
I mean, how does a cop leave his post

28:43.931 --> 28:46.092
and abandon his vehicle
and just walk away?

28:46.225 --> 28:48.716
If it was up to me,
they'd throw his ass in jail.

28:50.229 --> 28:52.606
You had to be there, I guess.

28:52.732 --> 28:55.394
After Katrina we got hit with Rita
and we didn't loot,

28:55.526 --> 28:58.768
complain, go crazy or run away like y'all did.

29:00.031 --> 29:03.523
lt's open. Keys are inside. Have a nice trip.

30:06.973 --> 30:08.804
What, you're not taking the car?

30:08.933 --> 30:12.175
— Not myjob, I'm afraid.
— No? What the hell is it you do?

30:12.311 --> 30:15.178
Well, I'm from, uh, document retrieval.

30:15.314 --> 30:19.899
Vehicle retrieval will be here
and get that car, no problem.

30:20.027 --> 30:22.404
Your whole damn town's crazy,
you know that?

30:22.530 --> 30:25.863
You're preaching to the choir, officer. Preaching to the
choir!

30:25.992 --> 30:28.153
(Franklin) Got back in my house,

30:28.285 --> 30:31.027
this was the only thing left.

30:31.163 --> 30:33.154
This floated.

30:35.334 --> 30:37.290
I took it as a sign, Chief.

30:37.420 --> 30:40.002
We gotta mask this year.

30:40.131 --> 30:42.918
I started that one right before the storm.

30:43.050 --> 30:45.211
Still don't got nowhere
to hook up my suit though.

30:45.344 --> 30:47.255
My daughter asked me
to come back to Atlanta.

30:47.388 --> 30:50.300
But what am I gonna do in Atlanta, Albert?

30:50.433 --> 30:53.470
You can park your van right here.

30:53.602 --> 30:55.513
We can do an extra practice this week.

30:55.646 --> 31:00.231
— Who else back?
- George, Troy.

31:00.359 --> 31:03.772
— Ronnie coming from Memphis.
— He don't have nowhere to stay either.

31:03.904 --> 31:06.987
— Calliope closed.
— Yeah, I know.

31:07.116 --> 31:11.735
l was over there.
Well, he can stay with me too.

31:11.871 --> 31:13.953
So we're masking for Mardi Gras, right?

31:15.207 --> 31:17.368
You're damn right.

31:18.544 --> 31:20.626
— Did we have a job that night?
— That's not the point.

31:20.755 --> 31:23.542
— Oh, yeah? What is the point?
— I'm saying that if you're playing

31:23.674 --> 31:25.665
with every fucking band
on Frenchmen Street,

31:25.801 --> 31:28.417
it dilutes what we are doing.

31:28.554 --> 31:32.388
It's just a gig at the Spotted Cat.
I want to play, Sonny.

31:32.516 --> 31:35.633
— You're not hearing a fuckin' word I'm saying.
— I hear you.

31:35.770 --> 31:38.261
You're saying I can't play any gigs
except your gigs.

31:38.397 --> 31:41.730
— No, I'm not saying that.
— I'm supposed to watch you get high all day

31:41.859 --> 31:43.770
and then say no when people
want me on real gigs

31:43.903 --> 31:46.519
because you're worried it might ruin
what we're doing on the street?

31:46.655 --> 31:49.067
Passing around a fucking hat
for spare change?

31:56.832 --> 31:58.413
Ann.

31:59.460 --> 32:02.543
(Door opens, slams)

32:03.255 --> 32:05.246
(J‘ Band playing Quantum Time)

32:32.368 --> 32:35.451
— (Donald) So good to be back in New Orleans. —
(Applause)

32:37.790 --> 32:40.827
Yo, D, let's finish with
a little something from home.

32:40.960 --> 32:42.666
Nah, too easy.

32:42.795 --> 32:46.333
— I'm feeling like Coltrane, Giant Steps.
- OK.

32:49.969 --> 32:51.334
You go back to Paris.

32:51.470 --> 32:53.506
— You couldn't even get me a hotel room...
— (Larry sighs)

32:53.639 --> 32:56.096
I need something to blow up real soon.

32:57.143 --> 32:59.976
— Or a car chase.
- Sh, sh!

33:00.104 --> 33:01.685
(Phone ringing)

33:08.404 --> 33:10.816
- Hello?
— (Dominique) LaDonna?

33:10.948 --> 33:13.985
— Dominique? What's wrong?
— Your mama not doing well.

33:14.118 --> 33:15.824
l...| dropped by to look in on her.

33:15.953 --> 33:19.241
— What do you mean, not doing well?
- She's having trouble breathing.

33:19.373 --> 33:22.831
— Did you call the ambulance?
— I thought to call you first.

33:22.960 --> 33:26.703
— Call the 911 now. Can she talk?
— Yes.

33:26.839 --> 33:29.125
She asked me for some water
and I gave it to her.

33:29.258 --> 33:31.874
Call the goddamn ambulance.
Have them take her to Touro.

33:32.011 --> 33:34.753
— I'll be there as soon as I can, OK?
- All right.

33:34.889 --> 33:38.598
Dominique, call them now,
as soon as I hang up the phone, OK?

33:38.726 --> 33:40.387
|wi||.

33:41.437 --> 33:42.847
lt's Mama.

33:42.980 --> 33:46.768
We gotta seriously talk about
moving her up here, LaDonna.

33:46.901 --> 33:48.892
I'll call you when | get to the hospital.

33:49.028 --> 33:51.064
Drive safe.

33:55.951 --> 33:58.067
This was a great night.

33:58.204 --> 34:02.197
I really felt like
we were all working as a team.

34:02.333 --> 34:04.039
We've all been through a lot

34:04.168 --> 34:07.501
and I know how hard everyone in this room
has been working.

34:09.173 --> 34:13.758
I'm gonna have to ask something now
that I never thought I'd have to ask.

34:13.886 --> 34:16.753
I know how hard it is right now.

34:16.889 --> 34:20.677
I need to ask if you all
would be willing to go a week...

34:28.234 --> 34:30.350
I can't do it, Jacques.

34:31.612 --> 34:35.855
I mean, even if I did, even if everyone agreed, it wouldn't
solve the problem, right?

34:35.991 --> 34:39.404
I'd just be putting it off,
kicking it down the road.

34:40.913 --> 34:42.619
I can't make expenses

34:42.748 --> 34:45.956
and we're gonna have to suspend operations.

34:47.086 --> 34:49.293
Maybe for a couple of weeks, maybe...

34:49.421 --> 34:51.412
maybe for good.

34:53.133 --> 34:55.340
I'm not gonna ask you to work without pay.

34:55.469 --> 34:57.460
I can't.

34:58.847 --> 35:00.974
I know y'all will find jobs again right away.

35:01.767 --> 35:03.678
Everyone needs help.

35:05.271 --> 35:07.683
l'll hope that when we get
back up and running again

35:07.815 --> 35:10.306
you'll be able to come back.

35:15.114 --> 35:17.446
I think I'm gonna be sick. Excuse me.

35:24.456 --> 35:26.447
(Laughter)

35:27.251 --> 35:30.243
- The first set was on fire.
— Hey, doing the best we can.

35:30.379 --> 35:32.370
(Delmond) You know my daddy, right?

35:32.506 --> 35:34.167
Big Chief Albert.

35:34.300 --> 35:36.507
Big Chief Donald, yeah.

35:36.635 --> 35:41.049
Man, I had such a great time
playing with your son, baby boy.

35:41.181 --> 35:43.718
Yeah, y'all sound good together, real good.

35:43.851 --> 35:46.843
— Oh, you was listening?
- I heard every note.

35:46.979 --> 35:49.345
Chief, you coming out this year?

35:49.481 --> 35:53.690
— Well, whoever makes it, we'll be out there.
- Mm, I'm in the same boat as you.

35:53.819 --> 35:56.310
I know you're making that walk
with your dad this year.

35:56.447 --> 35:58.483
I leave first thing Monday.

35:58.615 --> 36:02.028
(Donald) All right. I guess I'll have
to holler at you back in New York.

36:02.161 --> 36:05.028
All right, cool, cool. Uh, you ready?

36:05.164 --> 36:07.155
Yeah, let's do it, man. Chief.

36:07.291 --> 36:10.158
— And you, baby.
— I'm looking for you.

36:10.294 --> 36:11.704
(Albert laughs)

36:11.837 --> 36:15.000
Practice is at eight o'clock tomorrow night.

36:15.132 --> 36:17.293
You ain't gonna stay for the next set?

36:17.426 --> 36:20.418
Ah, I got work to do. I'll see you then.

36:21.889 --> 36:24.505
Hey, D. Good to see you back.

36:27.644 --> 36:30.807
— I felt like I couldn't stand up.
— She knows that.

36:30.939 --> 36:34.227
We're trying to find out
what other medicines you...

36:34.360 --> 36:37.397
She was on the Diabinese for diabetes.

36:37.529 --> 36:40.145
— Diabinese. Was she taking that daily?
— Yes.

36:40.282 --> 36:42.568
— Where's Dominique?
— I sent her home. It's late.

36:42.701 --> 36:44.237
How late is it?

36:44.370 --> 36:46.326
A quarter to three.

36:46.455 --> 36:49.117
We can go as soon
as we finish here, Mama.

36:49.249 --> 36:51.865
They said you might have just had
a little low blood sugar.

36:52.002 --> 36:53.867
— You're all right.
- We can go?

36:54.004 --> 36:55.835
— Just a while.
— Does your pharmacy

36:55.964 --> 36:57.795
have any record of your mother's medications?

36:57.925 --> 36:59.916
They're closed.

37:00.052 --> 37:02.885
I don't know if they're coming back.

37:22.991 --> 37:25.027
Hi. May I take your order, please?

37:25.160 --> 37:26.741
Cafe au lait and beignets, please.

37:26.870 --> 37:29.486
Cafe au lait and beignets? Thank you.

37:54.148 --> 37:56.139
Thank you.

38:11.623 --> 38:13.534
(Creighton) Well, that's good news, right?

38:13.667 --> 38:16.830
I don't see how they can deny the writ now. They'll have to
find him.

38:16.962 --> 38:21.001
The bureaucracy loves
paper evidence, forms.

38:21.133 --> 38:23.465
They get really wet if it's a triplicate.

38:24.678 --> 38:27.465
— LaDonna must be thrilled.
— I haven't spoken to her yet.

38:27.598 --> 38:31.967
I left a message, but I think maybe
she went to Baton Rouge for the weekend.

38:32.686 --> 38:34.927
Pretty great, huh?

38:35.898 --> 38:38.480
Wow! That's quite the getup.

38:38.609 --> 38:41.021
— She finished that costume yesterday.
- Aw.

38:41.153 --> 38:44.520
- Guess what I am.
— Um, a space alien.

38:44.656 --> 38:46.487
- No.
